author: BBC News
description:
"Embarrassing".
 
That’s how Football Manager’s top boss described cancelling the 2025 edition of the game.
 
The latest instalment in the popular franchise was delayed last year and then scrapped completely in February, leaving fans furious.
 
In an interview with BBC Newsbeat, Miles Jacobson revealed how “things went wrong” while the game was being developed and that if they released it in the state it was in, “it would have damaged us forever”.
 
He also added that “it was the most expensive decision” the studio has ever made and that the cancellation has had an impact on what the studio has been able to put into FM26.

author: BBC News
description:
Russia launched a "massive" overnight attack on Ukraine's southern and central regions, authorities said.
 
One woman was killed in Zaporizhzhia and 28 people were injured - including three children - according to local officials.
 
In Dnipropetrovsk, Governor Serhiy Lysak said overnight the region was "under massive attack" as he warned people to take cover, in what was the second successive night the region was targeted.
 
Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky said Moscow launched more than 500 drones and 45 missiles, hitting 14 regions across the country.
 
Meanwhile, Ukraine's military said it hit Russia's Krasnodar and Syzran oil refineries overnight.

author: BBC News
description:
A US appeals court has ruled that most tariffs issued by US President Donald Trump are illegal, setting up a potential legal showdown that could upend his foreign policy agenda.
 
The ruling affects Trump's "reciprocal" tariffs, imposed on most countries around the world, as well as other tariffs slapped on China, Mexico and Canada.
 
But, the ruling will not take effect until 14 October to give the administration time to ask the Supreme Court to take up the case.
 
Trump criticised the appeals court and its ruling on Truth Social, saying: "If allowed to stand, this Decision would literally destroy the United States of America."
